Originally, temnospondyls were classified according to the structure of their vertebrae. Early forms, with complex vertebrae consisting of a number of separate elements, were placed in the suborder Rachitomi, and large Triassic aquatic forms with simpler vertebrae were placed in the suborder Stereospondyli. With the recent growth of phylogenetics, this classification is no longer viable. The basic rhachitomous condition is found in many primitive tetrapods, and is not unique to one group of temnospondyls. Moreover, the distinction between rhachitomous and stereospondylous vertebrae is not phylogenetically significant ; instead, each is derived. All modern vertebrates have complex vertebrae, deriving from a more primitive condition in which vertebrae were made up of multiple separate elements. In primitive amphibia exposed in several fossil deposits, there is a macroevolutionary transition between this single - element condition and two fused elements.
